a range from 0 to 100. Click on any space within this range and a bar will appear. Feel free to move that bar around to the number that best represents your answer.<\/span>","DataExportTag":"religiosity","QuestionID":"QID285","ChoiceDataExportTags":false}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID286","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":32,"NextAnswerId":1,"DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"religiosity_time","QuestionID":"QID286"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID287","SecondaryAttribute":"Would you describe yourself as a \"born-again\" or evangelical Christian?","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Would you describe yourself as a \"born-again\" or evangelical Christian?","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"MC","Selector":"SAVR","SubSelector":"TX","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Would you describe yourself as a \"born-again\" or evangelical Christian?","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"Yes"},"2":{"Display":"No"}},"ChoiceOrder":["1","2"],"Validation":{"Settings":{"ForceResponse":"OFF","Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Would you describe yourself as a \"born-again\" or evangelical Christian?","DataExportTag":"religion_bornagain","QuestionID":"QID287"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID289","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":40,"NextAnswerId":1,"DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"bornagain_time","QuestionID":"QID289"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID301","SecondaryAttribute":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"You reported that you are currently living in <b>${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/b>, one of several states with <strong>high or recurrent flood risk<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"You reported that you are currently living in <strong>${q:\/\/QID300\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/strong>, one of several states with <strong>high or recurrent flood risk<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DataExportTag":"practical_flood_intr","QuestionID":"QID301"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID305","SecondaryAttribute":"Predicting Floods Before They Strike \u00a0 In many parts of the United States, floods have become a v..","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-310e7eab-7fff-4461-3431-39d46ffcf956\">Predicting Floods Before They Strike<\/b><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In many parts of the United States, floods have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy rainfall that overwhelms drainage systems or causes rivers to rise can happen quickly and without obvious warning. Flash floods and river floods have caused damage to homes, road closures, power outages, and even loss of life. Events like the 2025 Central Texas floods showed that dangerous floods can strike almost anywhere. For many families, these events are no longer something that happens &ldquo;somewhere else&rdquo; &ndash; they happen close to home.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To help communities prepare, climate scientists at the National Severe Storms Laboratory (NSSL), part of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), work on improving how floods and flash floods are predicted and warned against. They study heavy rainfall and use radar and sensor data to estimate how much rain will fall and where flooding is likely to happen. This research supports forecasting tools such as the Multi-Radar Multi-Sensor system and the FLASH flash-flood model, which help forecasters issue earlier and more accurate flood warnings.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For these tools, climate researchers combine data from radar, satellites, and rain gauges, to show how rain is spreading and how water may move across the ground. This gives National Weather Service forecasters better information to send flood watches and warnings, giving people, emergency services, and local officials more time to prepare before dangerous water arrives.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Together, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving flood forecasts and early-warning systems &ndash; helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.&nbsp;<\/p>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Predicting Floods Before They Strike \u00a0 In many parts of the United States, floods have become a v...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":9,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-310e7eab-7fff-4461-3431-39d46ffcf956\">Predicting Floods Before They Strike<\/b><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In many parts of the United States, floods have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy rainfall that overwhelms drainage systems or causes rivers to rise can happen quickly and without obvious warning. Flash floods and river floods have caused damage to homes, road closures, power outages, and even loss of life. Events like the 2025 Central Texas floods showed that dangerous floods can strike almost anywhere. For many families, these events are no longer something that happens &ldquo;somewhere else&rdquo; &ndash; they happen close to home.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To help communities prepare, climate scientists at the National Severe Storms Laboratory (NSSL), part of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), work on improving how floods and flash floods are predicted and warned against. They study heavy rainfall and use radar and sensor data to estimate how much rain will fall and where flooding is likely to happen. This research supports forecasting tools such as the Multi-Radar Multi-Sensor system and the FLASH flash-flood model, which help forecasters issue earlier and more accurate flood warnings.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For these tools, climate researchers combine data from radar, satellites, and rain gauges, to show how rain is spreading and how water may move across the ground. This gives National Weather Service forecasters better information to send flood watches and warnings, giving people, emergency services, and local officials more time to prepare before dangerous water arrives.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Together, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving flood forecasts and early-warning systems &ndash; helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.&nbsp;<\/p>","DataExportTag":"practical_flood_text","QuestionID":"QID305"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID309","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":52,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"practical_flood_time","QuestionID":"QID309"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID316","SecondaryAttribute":"Detecting Wildfires Before They Spread \u00a0 In many parts of the United States, wildfires have becom..","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-a7bc4437-7fff-2357-dba7-df1573eb5534\">Detecting Wildfires Before They Spread<\/b><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In many parts of the United States, wildfires have become a very real and nearby threat. Fire seasons that once lasted a few weeks now stretch across several months, and even regions that rarely burned before are now facing fast-moving blazes. Wildfires have erased homes, and even caused loss of life. Events like the January 2025 Southern California wildfires showed that, in addition to dangers posed by flames, smoke and ash can travel hundreds of miles, turning skies orange and threatening people\u2019s health. For many families, wildfires are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To help communities prepare, climate scientists from the U.S. Department of Homeland Security and NASA are developing new early-detection systems that can spot wildfires minutes after they begin. Using satellite images, heat sensors, and artificial-intelligence models, these systems detect the first signs of smoke or fire and alert local emergency managers right away. Their work has already helped firefighters in several western states reach ignition sites faster and prevent small blazes from becoming major disasters.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Climate researchers are also improving forecasts that show where and when dangerous fire conditions are likely to develop. This gives park rangers, energy companies, and residents more time to clear vegetation, secure equipment, or plan evacuations before a fire starts.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Together, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving wildfire forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.<\/p>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Detecting Wildfires Before They Spread \u00a0 In many parts of the United States, wildfires have becom...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":9,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-a7bc4437-7fff-2357-dba7-df1573eb5534\">Detecting Wildfires Before They Spread<\/b><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In many parts of the United States, wildfires have become a very real and nearby threat. Fire seasons that once lasted a few weeks now stretch across several months, and even regions that rarely burned before are now facing fast-moving blazes. Wildfires have erased homes, and even caused loss of life. Events like the January 2025 Southern California wildfires showed that, in addition to dangers posed by flames, smoke and ash can travel hundreds of miles, turning skies orange and threatening people\u2019s health. For many families, wildfires are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To help communities prepare, climate scientists from the U.S. Department of Homeland Security and NASA are developing new early-detection systems that can spot wildfires minutes after they begin. Using satellite images, heat sensors, and artificial-intelligence models, these systems detect the first signs of smoke or fire and alert local emergency managers right away. Their work has already helped firefighters in several western states reach ignition sites faster and prevent small blazes from becoming major disasters.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Climate researchers are also improving forecasts that show where and when dangerous fire conditions are likely to develop. This gives park rangers, energy companies, and residents more time to clear vegetation, secure equipment, or plan evacuations before a fire starts.<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><\/p>\n\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Together, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving wildfire forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.<\/p>","DataExportTag":"practical_fire_text","QuestionID":"QID316"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID319","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":36,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"practical_fires_time","QuestionID":"QID319"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID322","SecondaryAttribute":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"You reported that you are currently living in <strong>${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/strong>, one of several states with <strong>high or increasing wildfire risk<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"You reported that you are currently living in <strong>${q:\/\/QID320\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/strong>, one of several states with <strong>high or increasing wildfire risk<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DataExportTag":"practical_fire_intro","QuestionID":"QID322"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID323","SecondaryAttribute":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"You reported that you are currently living in <strong>${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/strong>, one of several states with <strong>severe cold, snow, ice, or blizzards<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"You reported that you are currently living in ${q:\/\/QID1721185837\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}, o...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"You reported that you are currently living in <strong>${q:\/\/QID320\/ChoiceGroup\/SelectedChoices}<\/strong>, one of several states with <strong>severe cold, snow, ice, or blizzards<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DataExportTag":"practical_ice_intro","QuestionID":"QID323"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID327","SecondaryAttribute":"Forecasting Winter Storms Before They Strike In many parts of the United States, severe winter st...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<strong>Forecasting Winter Storms Before They Strike <\/strong><br>\n<br>\n<br>\nIn many parts of the United States, severe winter storms have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy snowfall, freezing rain, and sudden cold snaps have caused power outages, road closures, and even loss of life. Events like the 2021 Texas freeze and the 2022 Buffalo blizzard showed that dangerous winter weather can strike almost anywhere. For many families, these storms are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<br><br>\nTo help communities prepare, climate scientists at the National Weather Service and several U.S. universities are developing new forecasting systems that can predict blizzards and extreme cold days to weeks in advance. Using satellite data, radar observations, and high-resolution climate models, they identify patterns in the atmosphere that signal when and where dangerous storms are likely to form. Their work has already helped local authorities issue warnings earlier and protect residents and infrastructure before conditions worsen.<br><br>\nClimate researchers are also working with city planners and emergency agencies to translate forecasts into concrete actions \u2013 salting roads, securing power lines, or warning schools and hospitals in time to prepare.<br><br>\nTogether, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving winter storm forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping to protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Forecasting Winter Storms Before They Strike In many parts of the United States, severe winter st...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<strong>Forecasting Winter Storms Before They Strike <\/strong><br>\n<br>\n<br>\nIn many parts of the United States, severe winter storms have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy snowfall, freezing rain, and sudden cold snaps have caused power outages, road closures, and even loss of life. Events like the 2021 Texas freeze and the 2022 Buffalo blizzard showed that dangerous winter weather can strike almost anywhere. For many families, these storms are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<br><br>\nTo help communities prepare, climate scientists at the National Weather Service and several U.S. universities are developing new forecasting systems that can predict blizzards and extreme cold days to weeks in advance. Using satellite data, radar observations, and high-resolution climate models, they identify patterns in the atmosphere that signal when and where dangerous storms are likely to form. Their work has already helped local authorities issue warnings earlier and protect residents and infrastructure before conditions worsen.<br><br>\nClimate researchers are also working with city planners and emergency agencies to translate forecasts into concrete actions \u2013 salting roads, securing power lines, or warning schools and hospitals in time to prepare.<br><br>\nTogether, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving winter storm forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping to protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings.","DataExportTag":"practical_ice_text","QuestionID":"QID327"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID329","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":72,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"practical_ice_time","QuestionID":"QID329"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID334","SecondaryAttribute":"You are living in the United States, a country facing risks by more and more extreme weather even...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"You are living in the United States, a country facing risks <strong>by more and more extreme weather events<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"You are living in the United States, a country facing risks by more and more extreme weather even...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"You are living in the United States, a country facing risks <strong>by more and more extreme weather events<\/strong>. Please read the text on the following page carefully. It describes a real project in the U.S., working particularly on reducing the risks from these hazards by helping communities prepare for extreme weather.<br>","DataExportTag":"practical_us_intro","QuestionID":"QID334"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID338","SecondaryAttribute":"Improving Warnings for Extreme Weather Before It Strikes In many parts of the United States, extr...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<strong>Improving Warnings for Extreme Weather Before It Strikes <\/strong><br>\n<br>\n<br>\nIn many parts of the United States, extreme weather events have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy rain, flash floods, wildfires, and winter storms can damage homes and roads, and sometimes even lead to loss of life. Recent outbreaks of extreme weather have shown that dangerous conditions can arise with little time to react. For many families, these events are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<br><br>\nTo help communities prepare, climate scientists at NOAA\u2019s Hazardous Weather Testbed conduct research to improve how severe and hazardous weather is detected, analyzed, and warned against. In this testbed, researchers and operational National Weather Service forecasters work side by side to evaluate new tools, data, and warning technologies in a setting that closely mimics real forecasting offices. They test experimental radar, satellite, and modeling products during both live weather events and archived cases to see how these innovations perform in practice.<br><br>\nClimate researchers are refining systems that support faster, clearer, and more reliable warnings for extreme weather. By bringing together researchers, forecasters, and sometimes emergency managers, the Testbed helps ensure that new scientific advances are usable in real-world operations and truly meet the needs of those who protect the public.<br>\n<br>\nTogether, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving extreme weather forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings this season and in the years ahead.","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Improving Warnings for Extreme Weather Before It Strikes In many parts of the United States, extr...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<strong>Improving Warnings for Extreme Weather Before It Strikes <\/strong><br>\n<br>\n<br>\nIn many parts of the United States, extreme weather events have become a very real and nearby threat. Heavy rain, flash floods, wildfires, and winter storms can damage homes and roads, and sometimes even lead to loss of life. Recent outbreaks of extreme weather have shown that dangerous conditions can arise with little time to react. For many families, these events are no longer something that happens \u201csomewhere else\u201d \u2013 they happen close to home.<br><br>\nTo help communities prepare, climate scientists at NOAA\u2019s Hazardous Weather Testbed conduct research to improve how severe and hazardous weather is detected, analyzed, and warned against. In this testbed, researchers and operational National Weather Service forecasters work side by side to evaluate new tools, data, and warning technologies in a setting that closely mimics real forecasting offices. They test experimental radar, satellite, and modeling products during both live weather events and archived cases to see how these innovations perform in practice.<br><br>\nClimate researchers are refining systems that support faster, clearer, and more reliable warnings for extreme weather. By bringing together researchers, forecasters, and sometimes emergency managers, the Testbed helps ensure that new scientific advances are usable in real-world operations and truly meet the needs of those who protect the public.<br>\n<br>\nTogether, this work shows how climate scientists, working alongside forecasters, are improving extreme weather forecasts and early-warning systems \u2013 helping protect communities by giving them earlier and more reliable warnings this season and in the years ahead.","DataExportTag":"practical_us_text","QuestionID":"QID338"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID339","SecondaryAttribute":"Timing","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"Timing","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"Timing","Selector":"PageTimer","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","MinSeconds":"0","MaxSeconds":"0"},"QuestionDescription":"Timing","Choices":{"1":{"Display":"First Click"},"2":{"Display":"Last Click"},"3":{"Display":"Page Submit"},"4":{"Display":"Click Count"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":24,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Timing","DataExportTag":"practical_us_time","QuestionID":"QID339"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_b2ULL6XxhpfseDY","Element":"STAT","PrimaryAttribute":"Survey Statistics","SecondaryAttribute":null,"TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"MobileCompatible":true,"ID":"Survey Statistics"}}]}